Ad Text:
We are looking for a skilled AESCSF Consultant to support the rollout, evaluation, and ongoing enhancement of the Australian Energy Sector Cyber Security Framework. In this role, you’ll partner with stakeholders across the energy sector to uplift cyber maturity, ensure regulatory compliance, and embed industry‑aligned security practices.
  
Key Responsibilities

Perform AESCSF assessments to identify risks, gaps, and opportunities for improvement
Design and execute uplift strategies that strengthen cyber security maturity across operations
Provide expert advice on regulatory obligations and recognised best‑practice frameworks
Work collaboratively with technical teams, business leaders, and external partners to deliver secure, practical solutions
Produce clear reports, recommendations, and strategic roadmaps for senior stakeholders
Lead workshops and training sessions to build organisational capability in AESCSF practices
Stay across emerging threats, standards, and technologies relevant to the energy sector
  
About You

5+ years’ experience in cyber security, risk, or compliance consulting
Strong understanding of the AESCSF and its application within the energy industry
Knowledge of complementary frameworks such as ISO 27001, NIST CSF, or Essential Eight
Strong analytical, communication, and problem‑solving abilities
Able to translate technical insights into meaningful business outcomes
Confident engaging with senior stakeholders and regulatory bodies
Relevant certifications (CISSP, CISM, ISO Lead Auditor, etc.) are highly regarded
  
If you’re looking to contribute to a high‑impact initiative that directly supports national energy security, we’d love to hear from you.
Interviews will commence in January 2026.

In this exciting role as a BI Analyst, reporting to the General Manager Data & Analytics, you’ll engage with a variety of stakeholders, including the Executive leadership team, administrative staff, and care team members, to capture and define reporting requirements. This unique opportunity will empower you to craft comprehensive BI solutions, derive actionable insights, and spearhead our migration to a cloud-based infrastructure, all within the dynamic, innovative, and supportive atmosphere of our growing organisation.

About UNSW

At UNSW, we pride ourselves on being a workplace where the best people come to do their best work.  We aspire to be Australia’s global university, improving and transforming lives through excellence in research, outstanding education and a commitment to advancing a just society. 

Why your role matters

The Head of Research Data provides strategic leadership for UNSW’s institutional approach to research data governance, infrastructure, and stewardship. The role sets the strategic direction for how research data is created, managed, shared, and preserved in line with the University’s research integrity, compliance, and innovation objectives. It holds significant responsibility for ensuring enterprise-wide alignment in research data practices.

A pivotal element of the role is advancing UNSW’s research data strategy through frameworks, policies, and programs that embed the FAIR principles - making data Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, and Reusable. The position offers expert guidance to senior stakeholders, represents UNSW in national and international forums, and leads cross-functional initiatives with faculties, the Research Office, IT, the Library, and external partners.

Reporting to the Director, Data Management and with no direct reports, the role carries substantial strategic influence over the University’s research data management and governance approach.

About the Role               

The successful applicant will be required to undertake and have experience in the following areas of expertise:

Lead the development and implementation of UNSW’s Research Data Strategy and institution-wide governance frameworks, ensuring alignment with Digital, Data, and Research strategies.
Oversee the design, integration, and sustainability of enterprise research data systems, including repositories, catalogues, and preservation infrastructure.
Provide expert advice to executive leaders and committees on research data policy, risk, compliance, and capability development.
Champion FAIR principles and drive a culture of responsible research data stewardship across all disciplines.
Represent UNSW in national and international collaborations, influencing sector-wide research data initiatives.
Build institutional capability through training, communities of practice, and performance monitoring to enhance UNSW’s research data maturity.

About You 

Relevant tertiary qualifications (or equivalent experience) in information management, research administration, or a related field, supported by extensive practical experience.
Demonstrated capability to design and implement enterprise-level research data frameworks, infrastructure, and metadata standards, with strong knowledge of FAIR principles and major research data platforms.
Strong understanding of privacy, ethics, data sovereignty, and funder compliance requirements affecting research data management.
Proven experience delivering high-level strategic advice and influencing decision-making at executive and sector levels.
Advanced leadership, communication, negotiation, and stakeholder engagement skills across technical, research, and policy environments, including the preparation of strategic documents and reports.
Recognised expertise in research data management, with a commitment to data ethics, research integrity, continuous improvement, and alignment with UNSW’s values and standards.

For further information on the role & responsibilities, please refer to the Position Description

About UNSW

At UNSW, we pride ourselves on being a workplace where the best people come to do their best work.  We aspire to be Australia’s global university, improving and transforming lives through excellence in research, outstanding education and a commitment to advancing a just society. 

Why your role matters

The Master Data Management (MDM) Data Governance Manager provides leadership in designing, implementing and managing UNSW’s master and reference data governance framework to ensure data accuracy, consistency, compliance, and trust. The role drives the creation and enforcement of governance policies, standards, and stewardship practices that enable effective and responsible management of critical data across the University.

By translating governance principles into operational practice, the role oversees data ownership, quality measures, metadata standards, catalogue solutions, and compliance processes that underpin reliable analytics, reporting, and innovation. Working closely with stakeholders, the MDM Data Governance Manager resolves data quality and ownership issues, integrates governance into day-to-day operations, and ensures alignment with UNSW’s strategic priorities, regulatory obligations, and the Enterprise Data Office agenda. The position reports to the Head of Master Data Management and has no direct reports.

About the Role               

The successful applicant will be required to undertake and have experience in the following areas of expertise:

Lead the development, implementation, and continual enhancement of UNSW’s master data governance framework, policies, and standards in line with strategic and regulatory requirements.
Oversee data profiling, cleansing activities, and adherence to data quality and governance standards.
Provide guidance, escalation pathways, and accountability mechanisms to support data owners and stewards.
Develop and maintain metadata standards, catalogues, privacy and retention guidelines, business glossaries, and data dictionaries to ensure consistent data understanding and use.
Ensure governance practices comply with legal, regulatory, and institutional obligations, and prepare evidence and reporting for assurance and governance forums.
Partner with stakeholders to embed governance practices, resolve data ownership and quality issues, and build capability through training, toolkits, and awareness initiatives.

About You 

Tertiary qualifications (or equivalent experience) in information or data management, supported by extensive experience in large, complex organisations.
Proven expertise in data governance, master data management, and related disciplines, with strong knowledge of stewardship models, metadata, data quality, privacy, and records obligations.
Demonstrated ability to translate governance frameworks and policies into practical, business-as-usual processes.
Experience working with diverse stakeholders to embed governance practices and resolve data quality or ownership issues.
Excellent communication, facilitation, and influencing skills, with the ability to explain governance concepts clearly to non-specialist audiences.
Strong analytical and problem-solving capability, familiarity with higher-education regulatory requirements, and alignment with UNSW’s values and standards.

For further information on the role & responsibilities, please refer to the Position Description.

The Perth USAsia Centre. Create impactful content that informs, engages, and drives smarter decisions.
Full-time appointment on a fixed term basis to 30 June 2027 (possibility of extension).
Base salary range: $129,497 – $137,029 p.a. plus 12% superannuation.

About the area

The Perth USAsia Centre is a non-partisan and not-for-profit institution. Through research and educational activities, the Centre strengthens strategic thinking between Australia, the Indo-Pacific, and the United States and engages thought leaders to address challenges and opportunities in the Indo-Pacific region.

Based at The University of Western Australia, the Centre is an independent company and shares the values of the University. It has a strong commitment to personal effectiveness, working collaboratively and demonstrating a focus on results.

This position leads the Content and Analysis team, which is responsible for delivering high quality, insightful, and engaging content that educates stakeholders and empowers informed decision-making.

About the opportunity

Lead the planning, development, resource allocation and logistical coordination of the Centre’s content program.
Develop and foster relationships with key external stakeholders, research advisers, fellows, Centre partners and industry, research and government bodies.
Align the Centre’s content development with internationally focused issues impacting Australia’s the political, business and social environments.

About you

Relevant tertiary qualification or equivalent competency.
Extensive experience in international policy, foreign affairs or international relations.
Experience managing a team with multiple priorities and a demonstrated ability to provide effective leadership, motivation and direction to staff.
Demonstrated experience liaising with external stakeholders, with a working knowledge of government operations and diplomacy.

Special Requirements

A current National Police Clearance Certificate.
Occasional weekend and after-hours work.
